
Constructor in OOP

A constructor is a special member function of a class that is automatically called when an object is created.

Its main purpose is to initialize the object's data members.

// copy constructor (shallow copy and Deep copy )

Shallow Copy: Copies member values directly. For pointer members, only the memory address is copied, causing multiple objects to share the same memory.

Deep Copy: Allocates new memory and copies the actual contents so that each object has its own independent copy of the data

Dangling Pointer: A pointer that refers to a memory location that has already been deallocated or is otherwise no longer valid. Accessing it results in undefined behavior.
